This command does NOT create a pod.
Instead, it generates a YAML file for the pod.

ūüĒć Breakdown of each part
1ÔłŹ‚É£ kubectl run redis
	‚ÄĘ This tells Kubernetes:
‚ÄúCreate a Pod named redis‚ÄĚ
2ÔłŹ‚É£ --image=redis123
	‚ÄĘ The container inside the pod will use image:
redis123
	‚ÄĘ (It may not exist; this is just a name)
3ÔłŹ‚É£ --dry-run=client
	‚ÄĘ VERY IMPORTANT
	‚ÄĘ This means: Do NOT actually create the pod.
	‚ÄĘ Only simulate the creation on the client side.
	‚ÄĘ Used to generate YAML without applying it.
4ÔłŹ‚É£ -o yaml
	‚ÄĘ Output the pod definition in YAML format.
5ÔłŹ‚É£ > redis-definition.yaml
	‚ÄĘ Redirect the output into a file named:
redis-definition.yaml
So you are saving the pod YAML into a file instead of showing on screen.

