The deployment provides us with the capability to upgrade the underlying instances seamlessly using rolling updates undo changes and pause and resume changes as required .











ūüöÄ 1. Deployment Update
A Deployment is updated when you:
	‚ÄĘ Change the image
	‚ÄĘ Change replicas
	‚ÄĘ Change environment variables
	‚ÄĘ Change configuration
‚úĒ Update using kubectl set image
This is the most common update method in DevOps pipelines.

kubectl set image deployment/my-deploy my-container=myrepo/myimage:v2
This will:
	‚ÄĘ Start new pods using v2
	‚ÄĘ Gradually remove old pods
	‚ÄĘ Create a rolling update

‚úĒ Update using kubectl apply
If you modify YAML (Deployment file), apply it:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

‚úĒ View rollout status
Always check deployment status:

kubectl rollout status deployment/my-deploy

ūüĒĄ 2. Deployment Rollback
Rollback = return to the previous version of the Deployment.
Kubernetes stores Deployment revisions.

‚úĒ Step 1: Check rollout history

kubectl rollout history deployment/my-deploy
Example output:

REVISION
1
2
3

‚úĒ Step 2: Rollback to previous version

kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-deploy
This returns deployment to the last good state.

‚úĒ Step 3: Rollback to specific revision

kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-deploy --to-revision=2

ūüĎÄ 3. View current rollout
To monitor the update process:

kubectl get pods -w
-w = watch live updates.

‚ôĽ 4. Pause and Resume Deployment (Advanced)
Use when you want to make multiple changes safely.
Pause rollout:

kubectl rollout pause deployment/my-deploy
Make changes:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Resume:

kubectl rollout resume deployment/my-deploy

ūüĒ• 5. Real World Example
Update application to new image:

kubectl set image deployment/frontend frontend=nginx:1.27
Check rollout:

kubectl rollout status deployment/frontend
Something broke ‚Üí rollback:

kubectl rollout undo deployment/frontend

ūüß† 6. How Rolling Update Works (Simple Explanation)
	‚ÄĘ Kubernetes creates new pods
	‚ÄĘ Waits until new pods are healthy (ReadinessProbe)
	‚ÄĘ Slowly terminates old pods
	‚ÄĘ Keeps service running without downtime

ūüďĆ Important Interview Points
Deployment strategies:
	1. RollingUpdate (default)
	2. Recreate (delete old then create new)
Deployment stores revision history
